# Frontend Rules

## Architecture
- Keep UI components presentational; move side effects to hooks/services.
- Reuse shared components before creating new ones.
- Keep page-level state close to route pages; avoid global state unless needed.

## State and data fetching
- Use one source of truth for each feature (Redux slice or local state, not both).
- Handle loading, empty, and error states for every async view.
- Normalize API responses before storing in state when lists are large.

## UI and UX
- Mobile-first responsive behavior is required.
- Use accessible labels, roles, and keyboard-friendly interactions.
- Show clear feedback for async actions (pending, success, failure).

## Performance
- Prefer lazy loading for heavy routes/components.
- Avoid unnecessary re-renders with memoization only when measurable.
- Optimize images and avoid rendering large lists without pagination/virtualization.

## Code quality
- Keep components focused; split files that become hard to scan.
- Avoid inline business logic in JSX; extract helpers/hooks.
- Add tests for critical user flows and state transitions.
